y causes it to break, while the same setup works on another environment. \r\n\r\nWhat breaks is that after `composer install`, the file `extensions/vendor/autoload.json` has absolute paths, instead of relative ones. For example: \r\n\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n    \"bobdenotter/seo\": {\r\n        \"name\": \"bobdenotter/seo\",\r\n        \"path\": \"/home/xxx/domains/xxx.io/extensions/vendor/bobdenotter/seo\",\r\n        \"webPath\": \"â€¦\",\r\n        \"class\": \"â€¦\",\r\n        \"constraint\": \"^3.0\",\r\n        \"valid\": true\r\n    },\r\n    \"bolt/email-spooler\": {\r\n        \"name\": \"bolt/email-spooler\",\r\n        \"path\": \"/home/xxx/domains/xxx.io/extensions/vendor/bolt/email-spooler\",\r\n        \"webPath\": \"â€¦\",\r\n        \"class\": \"â€¦\",\r\n        \"constraint\": \"^3.3\",\r\n        \"valid\": true\r\n    },\r\n```\r\n\r\nFor now, quick workarounds: \r\n\r\n1) Try running `composer install; cd extensions; composer install --no-dev` a second time, to regenerate the `autoload.json` file.\r\n2) add `\"symfony/finder\": \"^2.8, !=2.8.37\"` to your `composer.json`'s require section, prior to running `composer update`. \r\n\r\nThe change that seems to have introduced this issue is here: https://github.com/symfony/symfony/pull/26337\r\n\r\nI'll update this issue, when there's news. ","score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bolt/bolt/issues/7427","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bolt/bolt","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bolt/bolt/issues/7427/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bolt/bolt/issues/7427/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bolt/bolt/issues/7427/events","html_url":"https://github.com/bolt/bolt/issues/7427","id":310229346,"number":7427,"title":"Incorrect generation for aliased thumbnails","user":{"login":"Boorj","id":2145313,"avatar_url":"https://avatars0.githubusercontent.com/u/2145313?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/Boorj","html_url"